{"title_page": "F\u00e9lix Malloum", "text_new": "{{Infobox President\n| name          = F\u00e9lix Malloum\n| native_name   = {{Nobold|{{lang|ar|\u0641\u0644\u064a\u0643\u0633 \u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645}}}}\n| image         = F\u00e9lix_Malloum.jpg\n| order         = 2nd [[President of Chad]]\n| primeminister = \n| vicepresident = [[Mamari Djime Ngakinar]]<br/>[[Hiss\u00e8ne Habr\u00e9]]\n| term_start    = April 15, 1975 \n| term_end      = March 23, 1979\n| predecessor   = [[No\u00ebl Milarew Odingar]]\n| successor     = [[Goukouni Oueddei]]\n| birth_date    = September 10, 1932 \n| birth_place   = [[Fort Archambault]], [[Chad]]\n| death_date    = {{dda|2009|06|12|1932|09|10}}\n| death_place   = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| spouse        = \n| party         = \n| religion      = \n<!--Military service-->\n|nickname     = \n|allegiance   = {{flag|France}}<br>{{flag|Chad}}\n|branch       = {{army|France}}<br>{{army|Chad}}\n|serviceyears = 1951 - 1960 (France)<br>1960 - 1979 (Chad)\n|rank         = [[Brigadier General]]\n|unit         =\n|commands     =\n|battles      = [[First Indochina War]]\n|awards       = \n}}\n\n'''F\u00e9lix Malloum''' or '''F\u00e9lix Malloum Ngakoutou Bey-Ndi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0644\u064a\u0643\u0633 \u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|Filiks M\u02bfal\u016bm}}''; September 10, 1932 &ndash; June 12, 2009) was a [[Chad]]ian politician. He attended the French military academy and saw action in Indochina and Algeria. He later served as an officer in the [[Chadian Military]] and a member of the ruling [[Chadian Progressive Party]] (PPT). In 1971, he became the Chief of General Staff with the rank of colonel and named Commander-in-chief of the Armed Forces in 1972. In July 1973, he was arrested and imprisoned by President [[Fran\u00e7ois (Ngarta) Tombalbaye|Fran\u00e7ois Tombalbaye]] on charges of conspiring against the government, but was released after a successful [[Chadian coup of 1975|coup-d'etat on April 13, 1975]]. He served as both President and Prime Minister of [[Chad]] until August 29, 1978, when [[Hiss\u00e8ne Habr\u00e9]] was appointed [[Prime minister|Prime Minister]] to integrate armed northern rebels into the government. However, he was unsuccessful and resigned from the presidency on March 23, 1979<ref>{{cite book|title=African countries and cultures : a concise illustrated dictionary|last=Hornburger|first=Jane|publisher=D. McKay Co|year=1981|isbn=0679205071|location=New York|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/africancountries00horn}}</ref> after signing the Kano Peace Agreement which allowed the rebels to form a provisional government.<ref>{{cite book|last1=M. Lentz|first1=Harris|title=Heads of States and Governments Since 1945|date=4 February 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134264902|pages=155\u2013156|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6HKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=Goukouni+Oueddei+born&source=bl&ots=YzraTTgGzS&sig=00EMn9t6Til1njNqvb7bNAY-Fnc&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nMalloum retired from politics and settled in [[Nigeria]]. He returned to the Chadian [[Capital (political)|capital]] [[N'Djamena]] on May 31, 2002, after 23 years in [[exile]]. Upon his return he was entitled to the various benefits allowed to former presidents; these benefits included a monthly stipend of 3,000,000 [[CFA francs]], a residence, and coverage of his health expenses, along with two vehicles and a driver.<ref>[http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/CENTRALE/tchad/tchadbios/251felixmalloun.htm \"F\u00e9lix Malloum: Retour \u00e0 N'Djamena de l'ancien pr\u00e9sident tchadien\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004065600/http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/CENTRALE/tchad/tchadbios/251felixmalloun.htm |date=2006-10-04 }}, ''Afrique Express'', N\u00b0 251, June 18, 2002 {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nMalloum died from [[cardiac arrest]] aged 76 on June 12, 2009 at the [[American Hospital]] in Paris, France.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/DEPAFP20090612T224242Z/-France-Deces-Jacques-Chirac-Hissene-Habre-Deces-de-l-ex-president-Felix-Malloum.html D\u00e9c\u00e8s de l'ex-pr\u00e9sident F\u00e9lix Malloum], ''[[Jeune Afrique]]'', June 13, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panapress.com/Chadians-pay-last-respect-to-late-ex-president-Malloum--13-526408-18-lang2-index.html|title=Chadians pay last respect to late ex-president Malloum|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.countrystudies.us/chad/ Country Study, Chad]\n*[http://www.tchadien.com/histoire.html Tchadien.com] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Heads of State of Chad|Head of State of Chad]]|before=[[No\u00ebl Milarew Odingar]]|after=[[Goukouni Oueddei]]|years=1975&ndash;1979}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{ChadPres}}\n{{ChadPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malloum, Felix}}\n[[Category:Heads of state of Chad]]\n[[Category:Chadian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Chadian Progressive Party politicians]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chadian exiles]]\n[[Category:Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]]\n[[Category:Fran\u00e7ois Tombalbaye]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Chad]]\n[[Category:People from Moyen-Chari Region]]\n[[Category:Chadian expatriates in Nigeria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox President\n| name          = F\u00e9lix Malloum<br>\u0641\u0644\u064a\u0643\u0633 \u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645\n| image         = F\u00e9lix_Malloum.jpg\n| order         = 2nd [[President of Chad]]\n| primeminister = \n| vicepresident = [[Mamari Djime Ngakinar]]<br/>[[Hiss\u00e8ne Habr\u00e9]]\n| term_start    = April 15, 1975 \n| term_end      = March 23, 1979\n| predecessor   = [[No\u00ebl Milarew Odingar]]\n| successor     = [[Goukouni Oueddei]]\n| birth_date    = September 10, 1932 \n| birth_place   = [[Fort Archambault]], [[Chad]]\n| death_date    = {{dda|2009|06|12|1932|09|10}}\n| death_place   = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| spouse        = \n| party         = \n| religion      = \n<!--Military service-->\n|nickname     = \n|allegiance   = {{flag|France}}<br>{{flag|Chad}}\n|branch       = {{army|France}}<br>{{army|Chad}}\n|serviceyears = 1951 - 1960 (France)<br>1960 - 1979 (Chad)\n|rank         = [[Brigadier General]]\n|unit         =\n|commands     =\n|battles      = [[First Indochina War]]\n|awards       = \n}}\n\n'''F\u00e9lix Malloum''' or '''F\u00e9lix Malloum Ngakoutou Bey-Ndi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0641\u0644\u064a\u0643\u0633 \u0645\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|Filiks M\u02bfal\u016bm}}''; September 10, 1932 &ndash; June 12, 2009) was a [[Chad]]ian politician. He attended the French military academy and saw action in Indochina and Algeria. He later served as an officer in the [[Chadian Military]] and a member of the ruling [[Chadian Progressive Party]] (PPT). In 1971, he became the Chief of General Staff with the rank of colonel and named Commander-in-chief of the Armed Forces in 1972. In July 1973, he was arrested and imprisoned by President [[Fran\u00e7ois (Ngarta) Tombalbaye|Fran\u00e7ois Tombalbaye]] on charges of conspiring against the government, but was released after a successful [[Chadian coup of 1975|coup-d'etat on April 13, 1975]]. He served as both President and Prime Minister of [[Chad]] until August 29, 1978, when [[Hiss\u00e8ne Habr\u00e9]] was appointed [[Prime minister|Prime Minister]] to integrate armed northern rebels into the government. However, he was unsuccessful and resigned from the presidency on March 23, 1979<ref>{{cite book|title=African countries and cultures : a concise illustrated dictionary|last=Hornburger|first=Jane|publisher=D. McKay Co|year=1981|isbn=0679205071|location=New York|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/africancountries00horn}}</ref> after signing the Kano Peace Agreement which allowed the rebels to form a provisional government.<ref>{{cite book|last1=M. Lentz|first1=Harris|title=Heads of States and Governments Since 1945|date=4 February 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134264902|pages=155\u2013156|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6HKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA156&lpg=PA156&dq=Goukouni+Oueddei+born&source=bl&ots=YzraTTgGzS&sig=00EMn9t6Til1njNqvb7bNAY-Fnc&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nMalloum retired from politics and settled in [[Nigeria]]. He returned to the Chadian [[Capital (political)|capital]] [[N'Djamena]] on May 31, 2002, after 23 years in [[exile]]. Upon his return he was entitled to the various benefits allowed to former presidents; these benefits included a monthly stipend of 3,000,000 [[CFA francs]], a residence, and coverage of his health expenses, along with two vehicles and a driver.<ref>[http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/CENTRALE/tchad/tchadbios/251felixmalloun.htm \"F\u00e9lix Malloum: Retour \u00e0 N'Djamena de l'ancien pr\u00e9sident tchadien\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004065600/http://www.afrique-express.com/archive/CENTRALE/tchad/tchadbios/251felixmalloun.htm |date=2006-10-04 }}, ''Afrique Express'', N\u00b0 251, June 18, 2002 {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\nMalloum died from [[cardiac arrest]] aged 76 on June 12, 2009 at the [[American Hospital]] in Paris, France.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/DEPAFP20090612T224242Z/-France-Deces-Jacques-Chirac-Hissene-Habre-Deces-de-l-ex-president-Felix-Malloum.html D\u00e9c\u00e8s de l'ex-pr\u00e9sident F\u00e9lix Malloum], ''[[Jeune Afrique]]'', June 13, 2009 {{in lang|fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panapress.com/Chadians-pay-last-respect-to-late-ex-president-Malloum--13-526408-18-lang2-index.html|title=Chadians pay last respect to late ex-president Malloum|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.countrystudies.us/chad/ Country Study, Chad]\n*[http://www.tchadien.com/histoire.html Tchadien.com] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-